solution: ```class StockSpanner {
public:
    StockSpanner() {}

    int next(int price) {
        int span = 1;
        while (!st.empty() && st.top().first <= price) {
            span += st.top().second;
            st.pop();
        }
        st.emplace(price, span);
        return span;
    }

private:
    stack<pair<int, int>> st;
};

/**
 * Your StockSpanner object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * StockSpanner* obj = new StockSpanner();
 * int param_1 = obj->next(price);
 */```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1) amortized per next() call
space complexity: O(n) where n is the number of next() calls
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses a monotonic stack to store (price, span) pairs. Each price is pushed and popped at most once, giving amortized O(1) per call. The span for the current price is accumulated by merging previous smaller or equal prices in one pass.

